				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Heh.  It's actually normally a rule NOT to use multiple peripherals at once because it cuts the potential audience down to whoever has all the required peripherals.  I'm just dodging that rule<br />a. because I'm not planning to profit anyway<br />b. because anyone who kept a working NES around this long is probably a collector with peripherals anyway<br />c. because I want to.<br /><br />Iirc, the high-level theory on the 4-way adapter is that it just interleaves the serial streams from the inputs, however I've never actually played with one to be sure.  If it passes through all pins, there's nothing stopping combining peripherals, but each one has a quirk, so certain combinations of devices and ports may work better than others.  Iirc, the light gun uses the standard data pin but operates asynchronously (ignores the latch signal), the Pad uses a combination of 2 nonstandard pins but by doing so fits itself into 1 standard 8-bit read, and the Glove coerces itself into the standard pins but operates bidirectionally in a timing-dependent manner and, when in full boogie, sends many bytes of data.  So it really will boil down to whether the 4-ways pass through or buffer, what pins, and what precisely they do/expect with the latch.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Psych Software- failing to profit from retro/indie development since before it was cool<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.psychsoftware.org">http://www.psychsoftware.org</a><!-- m --></div>
